    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Fungi to files</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Iron Mountain didn’t begin as a high-security storage facility, but as a mushroom cultivation farm. In 1936, a German-American entrepreneur, <strong>Herman Knaust, bought a depleted iron ore mine in Kingston, New York, for $9,000</strong>. Herman Knaust and his brother Henry launched Knaust Brothers Inc., and at one point, they were the world’s largest mushroom growers and canners. Herman was even nicknamed the “Mushroom King of America.”
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/vintage-truck-knausts-cavern-mushrooms-mine.png" alt="A vintage truck of Knausts Cavern Mushrooms stands before their mine" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>A vintage truck of "Knaust's Cavern Mushrooms" stands before their mine. Credits: Iron Mountain</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">However, as global mushroom markets expanded, cheaper European and Asian imports rolled in, and the fungi empire declined. By 1950, the mushroom market shifted, and Knaust searched for alternative uses for his mine, which he had already named “Iron Mountain.” Ever the opportunist and a master of adaptation, <strong>Herman Knaust noticed the growing Cold War paranoia and rising concerns about data security</strong>. So, he boldly rebranded the site as a bomb-resistant storage facility.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Herman Knaust bought a 28-ton vault door from Ohio, and <strong>by 1951, he pitched Iron Mountain as the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-19-04-2025-most-secured-place-on-earth?source=website" target="_blank">most secure place on Earth</a> to store anything from priceless documents to sensitive government files</strong>. Though they were successful through the ‘60s, Iron Mountain faced rocky monetary ground by the early 1970s and was acquired by Vincent J. Ryan through Schooner Capital.  Ryan championed Knaust’s adaptation and reinvention spirit and ushered the humble operations into the digital era. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
